I moved with my son
recently to Chicago as well,

00:37:23.230 --> 00:37:25.010
and I wanted to
ask you privately

00:37:25.010 --> 00:37:29.075
what do you enjoy most about
the city outside of football.

00:37:29.075 --> 00:37:31.350
BASTIAN SCHWEINSTEIGER:
I enjoy the most of--

00:37:34.160 --> 00:37:38.750
I walk a lot with my family
around the Lincoln Park area--

00:37:38.750 --> 00:37:39.410
the zoo.

00:37:39.410 --> 00:37:44.540
My son loves these animals,
and elephants, and stuff.

00:37:44.540 --> 00:37:49.370
But I also like a lot that
here is a lake close by

00:37:49.370 --> 00:37:52.580
and you can take, for
example, the bikes

00:37:52.580 --> 00:37:54.050
and then go along the lake.

00:37:54.050 --> 00:37:58.400
That's beautiful-- and
very nice restaurants,

00:37:58.400 --> 00:38:00.590
I think, here as well.

00:38:00.590 --> 00:38:02.420
And what else do I like?

00:38:02.420 --> 00:38:04.687
I love the botanical garden.

00:38:04.687 --> 00:38:05.270
Have you been?

00:38:05.270 --> 00:38:06.080
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:38:06.080 --> 00:38:07.260
We just went last weekend.

00:38:07.260 --> 00:38:08.530
BASTIAN SCHWEINSTEIGER:
Here we go.

00:38:08.530 --> 00:38:10.030
STEFAN SCHMAGER: How
about Chicago deep dish?

00:38:10.030 --> 00:38:12.326
BASTIAN SCHWEINSTEIGER: I
love the trees over there.

00:38:12.326 --> 00:38:14.680
STEFAN SCHMAGER: How about
Chicago deep dish pizza?

00:38:14.680 --> 00:38:18.622
BASTIAN SCHWEINSTEIGER: I tried
it once, but it is too much.

00:38:18.622 --> 00:38:20.830
STEFAN SCHMAGER: For the
first time when you have it,

00:38:20.830 --> 00:38:22.160
you think you can
eat a whole pizza,

00:38:22.160 --> 00:38:23.300
but then you
realize really quick

00:38:23.300 --> 00:38:24.250
that once slice is enough.

00:38:24.250 --> 00:38:25.246
BASTIAN SCHWEINSTEIGER:
That's true.

00:38:25.246 --> 00:38:26.788
AUDIENCE: I was
actually lucky enough

00:38:26.788 --> 00:38:30.080
to see you play against the
United States in Brazil.

00:38:30.080 --> 00:38:32.060
During that game, you
actually subbed out,

00:38:32.060 --> 00:38:35.310
so I'm not really sure if
you guys were trying or not.

00:38:35.310 --> 00:38:37.040
You're one of my
favorite players,

00:38:37.040 --> 00:38:40.320
but question about the different
leagues you've been a part of.

00:38:40.320 --> 00:38:42.530
Obviously, two of the top
leagues in the world--

00:38:42.530 --> 00:38:44.577
MLS is, obviously,
up and coming.

00:38:44.577 --> 00:38:45.660
We'll go back to your son.

00:38:45.660 --> 00:38:48.013
Let's say he turns into
this amazing soccer player

00:38:48.013 --> 00:38:49.430
and he gets to
that age where he's

00:38:49.430 --> 00:38:53.480
10, 11, 12-- you can get picked
up by these clubs very early.

00:38:53.480 --> 00:38:55.640
Would you encourage
him to stay with MLS

00:38:55.640 --> 00:38:57.920
or seek something
across maybe in Europe?

00:39:00.370 --> 00:39:02.120
BASTIAN SCHWEINSTEIGER:
It's a lot of, if.

00:39:05.180 --> 00:39:07.160
For me, first of all,
I think that the MLS--

00:39:07.160 --> 00:39:10.880
if the people who
work for the MLS

00:39:10.880 --> 00:39:17.600
are making the right decisions,
you can create a huge league.

00:39:17.600 --> 00:39:20.570
I know that all the
players in Europe,

00:39:20.570 --> 00:39:22.520
they come over to
the United States

00:39:22.520 --> 00:39:25.560
and then go for vacations in
a lot of cities over there.

00:39:25.560 --> 00:39:29.360
And if you can somehow
use the opportunity

00:39:29.360 --> 00:39:32.090
and use the potential
which you have here

00:39:32.090 --> 00:39:37.070
to create a great
league, you can

00:39:37.070 --> 00:39:39.570
even up with the leagues
in Europe, I think.

00:39:39.570 --> 00:39:42.300
And, of course, it takes
some years, for sure.

00:39:42.300 --> 00:39:46.730
But there's a
chance if my son is

00:39:46.730 --> 00:39:50.810
going to be in MLS or
Europe, I don't know that.

00:39:50.810 --> 00:39:51.860
I also don't know if--

00:39:51.860 --> 00:39:56.115
maybe he gets the talent--

00:39:58.972 --> 00:40:00.180
I'm not a good tennis player.

00:40:00.180 --> 00:40:06.710
So if he gets my talent from
playing tennis, it's not good.

00:40:06.710 --> 00:40:08.222
Let's see how he ends up.

00:40:08.222 --> 00:40:09.930
STEFAN SCHMAGER: I
have another question.

00:40:09.930 --> 00:40:11.170
So we talked about--

00:40:11.170 --> 00:40:13.170
we touched on the time
after your active career.

00:40:13.170 --> 00:40:14.920
You said that coaching
is probably nothing

00:40:14.920 --> 00:40:16.113
you would want to pursue.

00:40:16.113 --> 00:40:18.530
We also talked about Michael
Jordan, who played basketball

00:40:18.530 --> 00:40:22.000
first and then he turned
into a baseball player.

00:40:22.000 --> 00:40:23.750
One of the things that
people may not know

00:40:23.750 --> 00:40:27.010
is that in your youth, you
were actually also a skier.

00:40:27.010 --> 00:40:29.420
You both played
soccer but also ski,

00:40:29.420 --> 00:40:34.760
and you pursued both
on a quite serious way.

00:40:34.760 --> 00:40:37.100
Can you tell us a bit
about your youth sports--

00:40:37.100 --> 00:40:40.553
how you picked
soccer over skiing?

00:40:40.553 --> 00:40:42.220
BASTIAN SCHWEINSTEIGER:
Yeah, it's true.

00:40:42.220 --> 00:40:46.166
My father was a skiing racer,
so actually first time I

00:40:46.166 --> 00:40:48.240
was in skis, I was like
2 and 1/2 years old.

00:40:48.240 --> 00:40:51.435
So I grew up like
close to the mountains,

00:40:51.435 --> 00:40:56.250
so that was ideal for me
being outside fresh air.

00:40:56.250 --> 00:40:59.075
And in winter I was skiing, in
summer I was playing soccer.

00:40:59.075 --> 00:41:00.450
But then there
was a moment I had

00:41:00.450 --> 00:41:03.450
to decide between
soccer and skiing,

00:41:03.450 --> 00:41:05.310
because I got kind
of the possibility

00:41:05.310 --> 00:41:08.760
to move to Bayern
Munich when I was 14.

00:41:08.760 --> 00:41:09.840
And then I had to decide.

00:41:09.840 --> 00:41:12.410
And it's not easy at
that age to decide,

00:41:12.410 --> 00:41:14.670
so it made it kind of simple.

00:41:14.670 --> 00:41:18.420
And when you are a
skiing racer, you

00:41:18.420 --> 00:41:20.520
have to carry all these skis.

00:41:20.520 --> 00:41:23.820
And it's always cold outside.

00:41:23.820 --> 00:41:25.020
It's not really enjoyable.

00:41:25.020 --> 00:41:26.940
You have to get up early
and all this stuff.

00:41:26.940 --> 00:41:28.740
In football, you
just take the cleats

00:41:28.740 --> 00:41:30.730
and you play with your friends.

00:41:30.730 --> 00:41:35.273
So then I decided
to go for soccer.

00:41:35.273 --> 00:41:37.440
STEFAN SCHMAGER: Another
question from the audience.

00:41:37.440 --> 00:41:40.528
AUDIENCE: Thank you so
much for being here today.

00:41:40.528 --> 00:41:42.570
I was wondering if there
were any special moments

00:41:42.570 --> 00:41:44.340
from your childhood
or your youth

00:41:44.340 --> 00:41:46.920
that you remember that were
important moments for you

00:41:46.920 --> 00:41:48.910
as a player or as an individual.

00:41:48.910 --> 00:41:51.480
And I was also curious if
you had any thoughts on how

00:41:51.480 --> 00:41:53.670
the United States might
improve their youth

00:41:53.670 --> 00:41:55.530
programs to be a more
competitive nation

00:41:55.530 --> 00:41:57.080
in the future.

00:41:57.080 --> 00:41:59.830
BASTIAN SCHWEINSTEIGER: Yes,
to your second question,

00:41:59.830 --> 00:42:03.860
I think there have to be
a rule where it says, OK,

00:42:03.860 --> 00:42:05.760
in every MLS team,
the lineup has

00:42:05.760 --> 00:42:07.880
to be players from
the United States--

00:42:07.880 --> 00:42:10.500
or in the squad
maybe six players.

00:42:10.500 --> 00:42:15.230
And also, for example,
Christian Pulisic,

00:42:15.230 --> 00:42:18.620
he plays for Borussia Dortmund.

00:42:18.620 --> 00:42:21.360
But the goal should
be for the MLS

00:42:21.360 --> 00:42:23.820
to keep the American
players in the league

00:42:23.820 --> 00:42:26.430
to make it more popular
for the people over here.

00:42:26.430 --> 00:42:33.000
So these kind of rules I
think is possible to do.

00:42:33.000 --> 00:42:38.370
But that's how
you would create--

00:42:38.370 --> 00:42:40.890
would make the league
higher and also you

00:42:40.890 --> 00:42:44.970
would keep the idols for the
kids in the United States

00:42:44.970 --> 00:42:46.470
where they can look up to.

00:42:46.470 --> 00:42:49.680
And, to the first question--

00:42:49.680 --> 00:42:51.250
the first question that--

00:42:51.250 --> 00:42:52.670
AUDIENCE: Childhood moments.

00:42:52.670 --> 00:42:54.087
BASTIAN SCHWEINSTEIGER:
Yes, there

00:42:54.087 --> 00:42:59.380
was a childhood moment
when I was 15 years old.

00:42:59.380 --> 00:43:04.140
I was 15, and I got an offer
from a different club--

00:43:04.140 --> 00:43:07.510
and it was not Munich, it
was more north Germany.

00:43:07.510 --> 00:43:11.100
And they offered
me a lot of money.

00:43:11.100 --> 00:43:14.220
And I could train with
the first team over there.

00:43:14.220 --> 00:43:17.130
And I remember that I had--

00:43:17.130 --> 00:43:22.050
in that time, my coach was
the son of Franz Beckenbauer.

00:43:22.050 --> 00:43:24.630
You all know Franz
Beckenbauer-- he has a son.

00:43:24.630 --> 00:43:27.850
And, unfortunately,
he died two years ago,

00:43:27.850 --> 00:43:30.240
but I had a good
relationship with him.

00:43:30.240 --> 00:43:32.820
And he told me look,
Basti, maybe you

00:43:32.820 --> 00:43:34.848
can earn more money
over there and you

00:43:34.848 --> 00:43:36.390
train with the first
team over there,

00:43:36.390 --> 00:43:39.480
but to go through the
youth team at Bayern Munich

00:43:39.480 --> 00:43:42.470
will give you more as a
player and as a person.

00:43:42.470 --> 00:43:43.740
And I did that.

00:43:43.740 --> 00:43:48.930
So, I am very, very
happy that I had a voice

00:43:48.930 --> 00:43:51.830
to talk to in that moment.

00:43:51.830 --> 00:43:54.183
STEFAN SCHMAGER: Good choice.

00:43:54.183 --> 00:43:55.630
AUDIENCE: I have a question.

00:43:55.630 --> 00:43:56.190
Can you please talk--

00:43:56.190 --> 00:43:57.370
BASTIAN SCHWEINSTEIGER:
Nice jersey, nice jersey.

00:43:57.370 --> 00:43:58.670
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:43:58.670 --> 00:43:59.170
Oliver Kahn.

00:43:59.170 --> 00:44:01.330
BASTIAN SCHWEINSTEIGER:
Oliver Kahn, here we go.

00:44:01.330 --> 00:44:03.870
AUDIENCE: Can you please
talk about how you prepare

00:44:03.870 --> 00:44:07.170
on gamedays physically
and, especially,

00:44:07.170 --> 00:44:09.720
mentally for big
games-- finals matches--

00:44:09.720 --> 00:44:13.203
what's your process before
you walk out onto the field?

00:44:13.203 --> 00:44:15.120
BASTIAN SCHWEINSTEIGER:
Yes before actually it

00:44:15.120 --> 00:44:18.630
starts during the
week, but I always

00:44:18.630 --> 00:44:23.830
try to eat the right way
two days before the game

00:44:23.830 --> 00:44:25.215
so I have a lot of energy.

00:44:27.840 --> 00:44:32.220
But then also before I go to
bed a day before the match,

00:44:32.220 --> 00:44:36.870
I always try to imagine
how the game could be.

00:44:36.870 --> 00:44:40.680
I always ask our kit man
which jerseys are the opponent

00:44:40.680 --> 00:44:44.370
playing and which jerseys are
we playing so I can imagine.

00:44:44.370 --> 00:44:45.927
We have red and
Borussia Dortmund

00:44:45.927 --> 00:44:47.010
plays yellow, for example.

00:44:47.010 --> 00:44:51.750
And then I try to think about
all the players on the field--

00:44:51.750 --> 00:44:55.020
what's their strengths,
what is their weakness.

00:44:55.020 --> 00:44:55.830
What do they like?

00:44:55.830 --> 00:44:58.318
Some they don't like
to run with the ball,

00:44:58.318 --> 00:44:59.860
some they like to
run with the ball--

00:44:59.860 --> 00:45:01.170
so these kind of things--

00:45:01.170 --> 00:45:04.360
to be ready for the
moment when it happens--

00:45:04.360 --> 00:45:07.290
and, actually, before it
happens that I'm ready.

00:45:07.290 --> 00:45:11.640
And I do this all the time.

00:45:11.640 --> 00:45:13.415
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:45:13.415 --> 00:45:14.790
STEFAN SCHMAGER:
This is probably

00:45:14.790 --> 00:45:16.540
one of the "Talks at
Google" with the most

00:45:16.540 --> 00:45:19.160
questions from the audience,
so thank you very much.

00:45:19.160 --> 00:45:21.940
AUDIENCE: Yeah, hi, Basti,
thanks for the opportunity.

00:45:21.940 --> 00:45:24.900
I'm also a huge fan of
Bayern Munich and yourself.

00:45:24.900 --> 00:45:28.620
I moved to Chicago a year
ago from Germany too,

00:45:28.620 --> 00:45:33.690
and I'm interested to know what
do you miss most about Germany?

00:45:33.690 --> 00:45:36.690
And also you have
played many games that

00:45:36.690 --> 00:45:42.330
went all the way to penalties
and you've shot many penalties,

00:45:42.330 --> 00:45:44.460
and I would like
to know what do you

00:45:44.460 --> 00:45:46.140
think when you go to the ball?

00:45:46.140 --> 00:45:50.130
Are there any thoughts at all,
or are you just cool enough

00:45:50.130 --> 00:45:53.580
to go and shoot?

00:45:53.580 --> 00:45:55.770
BASTIAN SCHWEINSTEIGER: Yeah.

00:45:55.770 --> 00:45:58.660
Usually the Germans always
win penalty shootouts.

00:45:58.660 --> 00:46:00.270
I actually only lost the one--

00:46:00.270 --> 00:46:02.850
2012 in the Champions
League Final, unfortunately.

00:46:02.850 --> 00:46:06.390
But when you walk from
the halfway line--

00:46:06.390 --> 00:46:09.070
from the middle line
towards the ball,

00:46:09.070 --> 00:46:12.075
it can happen that
you lose your--

00:46:12.075 --> 00:46:13.950
there are too many kids
here, I can't say it.

00:46:13.950 --> 00:46:20.250
But you get a little bit
nervous, which is normal,

00:46:20.250 --> 00:46:21.810
right?

00:46:21.810 --> 00:46:23.620
But it's very
important that you know

00:46:23.620 --> 00:46:25.620
what you're going to do
in this kind of moments.

00:46:25.620 --> 00:46:32.370
It's very important to
analyze also the goalkeeper

00:46:32.370 --> 00:46:34.080
before maybe if you
have the chance.

00:46:34.080 --> 00:46:36.330
If you are the first one,
you're a little bit unlucky.

00:46:36.330 --> 00:46:40.570
But that always
helped me-- and, yeah,

00:46:40.570 --> 00:46:45.650
have the power in your
mind to take that shot

00:46:45.650 --> 00:46:47.505
and take the responsibility.

00:46:47.505 --> 00:46:49.880
But it's sometimes when you
have 80,000 people around you

00:46:49.880 --> 00:46:53.120
and they boo you,
it's not easy--

00:46:53.120 --> 00:46:54.200
or it is quiet.

00:46:54.200 --> 00:46:56.390
I don't like when it's quiet--

00:46:56.390 --> 00:46:58.970
sometimes it's so quiet you
can hear everything dropping.

00:47:01.940 --> 00:47:05.690
And the other question was
what I'm going to miss.

00:47:05.690 --> 00:47:07.070
There's a special food.

00:47:07.070 --> 00:47:08.590
It's called Kaiserschmarrn.

00:47:08.590 --> 00:47:10.340
I don't know, you
probably know it, right?

00:47:10.340 --> 00:47:12.132
STEFAN SCHMAGER: How
would you describe it?

00:47:12.132 --> 00:47:14.660
BASTIAN SCHWEINSTEIGER:
It's a pancake--

00:47:14.660 --> 00:47:15.955
a thick pancake, but cut it.

00:47:15.955 --> 00:47:18.080
STEFAN SCHMAGER: It's a
scrambled pancake in a way,

00:47:18.080 --> 00:47:18.250
right?

00:47:18.250 --> 00:47:19.833
BASTIAN SCHWEINSTEIGER:
Yeah, exactly.

00:47:19.833 --> 00:47:22.610
And that's what I
loved, actually,

00:47:22.610 --> 00:47:23.930
when I was skiing races.

00:47:23.930 --> 00:47:26.920
So this kind of food was always
available on the mountains.

00:47:26.920 --> 00:47:27.440
AUDIENCE: I know that
from the mountains.

00:47:27.440 --> 00:47:29.148
BASTIAN SCHWEINSTEIGER:
Exactly, exactly.

00:47:29.148 --> 00:47:30.350
But I miss that one, yes.

00:47:30.350 --> 00:47:31.600
AUDIENCE: Thank you very much.

00:47:31.600 --> 00:47:33.017
BASTIAN SCHWEINSTEIGER:
Thank you.

00:47:33.017 --> 00:47:36.370
AUDIENCE: I'm nervous coming up
to the mic like a penalty kick.

00:47:36.370 --> 00:47:39.500
So this is my husband,
Stephan, and I'm so--

00:47:39.500 --> 00:47:41.660
thank you so much for
making this dream--

00:47:41.660 --> 00:47:45.510
I'm eight months pregnant,
so I'm also very.

00:47:45.510 --> 00:47:47.330
But thank you so
much for making--

00:47:52.910 --> 00:47:54.570
making his dream come true.

00:47:54.570 --> 00:47:56.760
OK, so I want Stephan--

00:47:56.760 --> 00:47:58.620
this is for you to give
Basti a little break

00:47:58.620 --> 00:47:59.832
to drink some water.

00:47:59.832 --> 00:48:01.290
Stephan, can you
share a little bit

00:48:01.290 --> 00:48:05.138
about how this moment came about
and the idea that sparked it?

00:48:05.138 --> 00:48:06.680
STEFAN SCHMAGER:
Yeah it's actually--

00:48:06.680 --> 00:48:08.307
Google is an amazing place.

00:48:08.307 --> 00:48:10.140
You come to Google and
see "Talks at Google"

00:48:10.140 --> 00:48:14.020
and how your colleagues
bring in writers and authors.

00:48:14.020 --> 00:48:17.580
So it's a very empowering
culture to just give it a shot

00:48:17.580 --> 00:48:20.005
and try to reach out
to the Chicago Fire

00:48:20.005 --> 00:48:22.380
and see if your favorite player
could come in for a talk.

00:48:22.380 --> 00:48:28.410
So, in that sense, I'm
really happy to be here,

00:48:28.410 --> 00:48:31.171
to embrace that Google
culture-- and, yeah,

00:48:31.171 --> 00:48:32.546
just very happy
to have you here.

00:48:32.546 --> 00:48:36.500
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:48:36.500 --> 00:48:37.860
STEFAN SCHMAGER: I also--

00:48:37.860 --> 00:48:41.880
so what she's referring
to is a moment in our life

00:48:41.880 --> 00:48:43.780
when you signed with
the Chicago Fire.

00:48:43.780 --> 00:48:46.170
It was a week before
my son was born.

00:48:46.170 --> 00:48:48.900
A week after my son was born,
I went to your first game

00:48:48.900 --> 00:48:51.540
at Toyota Park back then.

00:48:51.540 --> 00:48:53.910
And I got him a
Germany jersey hoping

00:48:53.910 --> 00:48:56.310
that you could sign it one day.

00:48:56.310 --> 00:48:57.570
And I tried really hard.

00:48:57.570 --> 00:49:03.300
I set my mind to do it,
and maybe after this talk,

00:49:03.300 --> 00:49:05.092
you could give one
more signature.

00:49:05.092 --> 00:49:07.050
BASTIAN SCHWEINSTEIGER:
No problem, no problem.

00:49:07.050 --> 00:49:08.960
For the next one as well, right?

00:49:08.960 --> 00:49:10.850
STEFAN SCHMAGER: Exactly.

00:49:10.850 --> 00:49:13.770
AUDIENCE: Well, one of the
things you mentioned is at 14,

00:49:13.770 --> 00:49:17.000
you already were
going for Bayern.

00:49:17.000 --> 00:49:23.490
And what's it like
knowing from a teenager,

00:49:23.490 --> 00:49:28.425
having kind of a plan,
and then A, doing it--

00:49:28.425 --> 00:49:30.300
